et life played out against a turbulent historical backdrop—a relationship that strikes a precarious balance between deep cultural skepticism and authentic love.Featuring the original Polish text and the English translation on facing pages, Dear Ms. Schubert is a highly original and appealing book from a poet who richly deserves a wide English-language readership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aPOETRY / European / General.2bisacsh  aAnna Swirszczynska.  aCzeslaw Milosz.  aEast European literature.  aEastern European literature.  aJulia Hartwig.  aNow.  aNowa Fala.  aPanna Schubert.  aPolish New Wave.  aPolish literature and culture.  aPolish poetry.  aPolish poets.  aPolish women writers.  aStanislaw Baranczak.  aTeraz.  aWislawa Szymborska.  aZbigniew Herbert.  acontemporary Poland.  acontemporary Polish literature.  amodern Poland.  apoetry in translation.  apostwar poetry, post Soviet Poland.  atranslations into English.  aworld literature.1 aDavidson, Robin.1 aNowakowska, Ewa Elżbieta.1 aZagajewski, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069120847340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691208473423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docu